Introduction
The Model Context Protocol (MCP) is a new standard for connecting AI assistants (like LLMs) with external data sources and tools in a uniform way. Since its introduction, a variety of frameworks have emerged to help developers build MCP servers more easily. In this post, we’ll evaluate eight MCP server frameworks — each in a different language or ecosystem — and compare them on ease of use, extensibility, performance, and community support. These frameworks include: EasyMCP (TypeScript), FastAPI-MCP (Python/FastAPI), FastMCP (TypeScript), Foxy Contexts (Go), Higress MCP (Go/Envoy), MCP-Framework (TypeScript), Quarkus MCP Server SDK (Java), and the Template MCP Server (TypeScript). We’ll highlight the pros and cons of each and recommend which to use for quick prototyping vs. production-grade scenarios.
EasyMCP provides an Express-like API to define MCP tools and resources with minimal boilerplate​
EasyMCP (TypeScript)
Ease of Use (Onboarding & DX):
Very easy — “hides the plumbing” with an Express-like API. Decorators auto-infer inputs. Minimal code to get started.
Extensibility (Plugins/Middleware):
Basic extensibility — define custom tools, prompts, etc. via code. Context object for logging. Lacks some advanced features (no SSE or sampling yet).
Performance & Scalability:
Moderate — runs on Node/Bun. Good for development; not optimized for heavy concurrent load (still in beta).
Ecosystem & Support:
Small but growing — ~94⭐ on GitHub. Created by community (Z. Caceres). Active development but beta-quality.
FastAPI-MCP (Python/FastAPI)
Ease of Use (Onboarding & DX):
Extremely easy — “zero-configuration” integration into FastAPI. Auto-discovers all existing API endpoints as MCP tools with one function call to mount.
Extensibility (Plugins/Middleware):
Leverages FastAPI’s ecosystem — reuse FastAPI middleware, authentication, and schemas. Allows adding custom MCP tools alongside auto ones.
Performance & Scalability:
Moderate — powered by FastAPI’s high-performance async server (Uvicorn). Python limits raw throughput compared to Go/Java but is sufficient for many use cases.
Ecosystem & Support:
Good adoption — ~395⭐ on GitHub. Well-documented and supported by the FastAPI community. Familiarity with FastAPI is a plus.
FastMCP (TypeScript)
Ease of Use (Onboarding & DX):
Easy & full-featured — straightforward API (e.g., server.addTool()) with minimal boilerplate. Comes with a CLI for development and testing.
Extensibility (Plugins/Middleware):
High extensibility — supports sessions, authentication, custom error handling, and logging out-of-the-box. Define tools, resources, and prompts with full control.
Performance & Scalability:
Good — Node.js backend but optimized. Supports SSE streaming and stateful sessions. Suitable for production loads, though Node is less performant than Go/Java.
Ecosystem & Support:
Strong community — ~706⭐ on GitHub. Many real-world examples, active maintainer, and community support through Discord and awesome lists.
Foxy Contexts (Golang)
Ease of Use (Onboarding & DX):
Moderate — provides a declarative Go API using dependency injection (built on Uber Fx). Go knowledge is required, but documentation includes examples.
Extensibility (Plugins/Middleware):
Very extensible — define each tool/resource as separate components with dependency injection. Supports injecting database clients and custom middleware-like behavior.
Performance & Scalability:
High — compiled Go service with excellent concurrency and low latency. Supports both stdio and SSE transports. Suitable for production scale.
Ecosystem & Support:
Niche but promising — ~70⭐ on GitHub. Maintained by strowk. Likely to attract Go developers needing performance, though with a smaller community compared to TS/Py options.
Higress MCP Server Hosting (Go with Envoy WASM)
Ease of Use (Onboarding & DX):
Steeper learning curve — not just a library, but a solution to host MCP servers in an Envoy-based gateway. Requires using Alibaba’s Higress gateway and writing a Go WASM plugin.
Extensibility (Plugins/Middleware):
Enterprise-grade extensibility — integrates with gateway features (authentication, rate limiting, logging) out-of-the-box. More about plugging into a robust gateway than custom code.
Performance & Scalability:
Very high — runs inside Envoy proxy (WASM). Inherits Envoy’s scalability and security. Great for production deployments with many services and strict controls.
Ecosystem & Support:
Backed by Alibaba’s Higress project. Enterprise support is expected; however, community use is relatively limited to those using Higress. Documentation is available in the Higress repo.
MCP-Framework (TypeScript)
Ease of Use (Onboarding & DX):
Very easy — CLI scaffolding (mcp create) sets up a new project in minutes. Auto-discovers tools/resources from your code with minimal manual wiring. Excellent documentation and developer experience.
Extensibility (Plugins/Middleware):
Flexible — offers base classes and abstractions to define tools, plus automatic loading. Built on the official MCP SDK, ensuring compatibility. Supports multiple transports (stdio, SSE, HTTP stream).
Performance & Scalability:
Moderate — runs on Node.js. Handles SSE and HTTP streaming well. Suitable for most use cases; heavy loads may need scaling similar to any Node app.
Ecosystem & Support:
Active and growing — ~456⭐ on GitHub. Created by Alex Andru with a supportive community through Discord and discussions. Quickly evolving with the MCP spec.
Quarkus MCP Server SDK (Java)
Ease of Use (Onboarding & DX):
Moderate — integrates into Quarkus projects using annotations (e.g., @Tool, @Resource). Requires Java familiarity, but Quarkus dev mode makes iteration fast. JBang support allows running servers without full build setup.
Extensibility (Plugins/Middleware):
Highly extensible — integrated as a Quarkus extension. Leverages Java’s ecosystem (database access, dependency injection, security frameworks). Supports both stdio and SSE transports via separate modules.
Performance & Scalability:
High — Java performance enhanced by Quarkus optimizations (Vert.x event loop). Can be compiled to native for low-footprint and fast startup. Suitable for enterprise-scale production.
Ecosystem & Support:
Backed by the Quarkus/Red Hat community. Officially documented with an active, albeit smaller, user base (~57⭐) that is expected to grow as enterprises adopt MCP.
Template MCP Server (TypeScript)
Ease of Use (Onboarding & DX):
Easiest initial setup — a one-command template generator (npm init @mcpdotdirect/create-mcp-server) creates a ready-to-run MCP server project. Comes with a default structure and scripts to start in stdio or HTTP mode. Perfect for learning or quick prototyping.
Extensibility (Plugins/Middleware):
Code extensibility — provides a scaffold with the official MCP TypeScript SDK. Add your own tools, resources, and prompts in the provided structure. No specific plugin system beyond editing the code as needed.
Performance & Scalability:
Moderate — runs on Node (or Bun). Dual transport support (stdio and HTTP) is included by default. Performance depends on how you implement your tools but is as efficient as the underlying SDK.
Ecosystem & Support:
Official starter maintained by the MCP community. Ensures best practices. It serves as a foundation rather than a complete long-term framework; updates must be manually incorporated into your project if needed.
Framework-by-Framework Analysis
1. EasyMCP (TypeScript) — “Absurdly Easy” MCP Servers
EasyMCP’s goal is to live up to its name by making MCP server development absurdly easy. It provides a high-level Express-like API for defining tools, resources, and prompts, hiding most of the MCP protocol boilerplate behind simple method calls. For example, you can annotate class methods with @Tool or @Resource decorators and EasyMCP will automatically expose them as MCP endpoints, inferring parameter schemas for you. This makes developer onboarding extremely quick – if you know basic TypeScript, you can get a server running with just a few lines. The framework also offers a Context object to handle things like logging or progress inside your tool implementations, further reducing the need to touch low-level details.
Pros:
EasyMCP shines in simplicity and developer experience. It lets you define only the “bare minimum” needed for a working server. Optional parameters have sane defaults or are inferred, so you’re not overwhelmed with configuration. The experimental decorator API takes this further by automating input schema generation. TypeScript support is strong, providing type safety to catch errors early. This makes EasyMCP great for quick prototypes or simple use cases, and for developers who want to avoid framework complexity.
Cons:
As of early 2025, EasyMCP is still labeled beta and lacks some advanced MCP features. Notably, it doesn’t yet support server-sent events (SSE) for streaming responses, nor MCP’s new sampling and notification mechanisms. If your use case requires these (e.g. streaming large outputs to the client), EasyMCP might not suffice until those features mature. Its focus on simplicity also means it forgoes an explicit plugin or middleware system — you typically just extend the base class with your own code. That’s flexible in a code sense, but less so for dropping in pre-built extensions. In terms of performance, EasyMCP runs on Node.js — adequate for moderate workloads, but heavy production traffic might reveal Node’s limitations. Given the project’s youth (~94 GitHub stars), the community is small, so support relies on the maintainers’ responsiveness.
Ideal use cases:
EasyMCP is ideal for developers who want to get an MCP server running with minimal fuss, such as hackathons, demos, or integrating one or two quick tools into an AI assistant. It’s also a nice learning tool for MCP, since its abstractions closely mirror the core concepts (tool, resource, prompt) without extra complexity. As the project matures to add missing features, it could become a solid choice for small-to-medium production services that value developer productivity over maximum throughput.
2. FastAPI-MCP (Python/FastAPI) — Expose APIs to AI with Zero Config
FastAPI-MCP takes a different approach: instead of being a standalone server framework, it acts as an extension to the FastAPI web framework. Its purpose is to let you automatically expose existing REST API endpoints as MCP tools with “zero configuration.” If you have a FastAPI app (a common choice in Python for building APIs), you can mount an MCP server onto it with a single call. The library will introspect all your defined FastAPI routes, and for each one, create a corresponding tool in the MCP interface (with the same path, input schema from Pydantic models, and even the same documentation). In essence, your API becomes immediately accessible to AI agents via MCP. FastAPI-MCP preserves schema and documentation of endpoints to present meaningful tool descriptions to the LLM, and it allows adding extra custom MCP tools not tied to an HTTP endpoint if needed.
