Pros:
The primary advantage here is convenience for Python developers. If you already have functionality in a FastAPI service (or plan to build one), you incur almost no extra work to enable MCP — it’s literally just point it at your app and it works. This makes it fantastic for quickly enabling AI access to an existing API. Developer onboarding is trivial since it leverages FastAPI knowledge and doesn’t introduce new paradigms. You also get to reuse FastAPI’s robust features — your authentication dependencies, middleware (logging, CORS, etc.), and error handling will still apply when the endpoints are called via MCP. Performance-wise, FastAPI is one of Python’s fastest frameworks (built on ASGI/Uvicorn), so while Python isn’t as fast as Go or Java, you can still handle decent loads with async concurrency. The project appears well-adopted with ~395 stars and an active repository, indicating a supportive community.
Cons:
Being tied to FastAPI is a double-edged sword — it’s excellent if you use FastAPI, but not useful if you’re not in that ecosystem. Unlike other frameworks, FastAPI-MCP doesn’t provide a structured way to build an MCP server from scratch; it assumes you have (or will have) a FastAPI app. In terms of extensibility, you’re constrained to FastAPI’s paradigms. While this is usually fine, you might not have MCP-specific hooks beyond what the library exposes. For example, if you wanted to implement an MCP-specific middleware (say, to transform all tool outputs), you’d have to weave it into FastAPI’s middleware or the tool functions themselves — there’s no plugin system in FastAPI-MCP itself. Another consideration is that automatic exposure of all endpoints could be too permissive; you may need to explicitly exclude some routes from the MCP view if they aren’t safe or relevant for the AI. Finally, scaling a Python server to very high load can be more costly (in terms of CPU) than a comparable Go/Java service, so for extreme performance requirements you might look to other frameworks.
Ideal use cases:
FastAPI-MCP is best when you want to leverage an existing API for AI agents quickly. For instance, an organization with existing REST services can use it to expose those endpoints to an AI agent without rewriting anything in a new language. It’s also great for Python enthusiasts prototyping AI agents: you can write some FastAPI endpoints and immediately test them as tools in an AI chat. For a pure-play new project focused only on MCP tools, you might not choose this; instead, you could opt for a Python framework that’s MCP-first or even a TypeScript solution.
3. FastMCP (TypeScript) — Full-Featured and “Fast” Server Development
FastMCP (TypeScript) is a dedicated MCP server framework that aims to combine ease of use with feature completeness. It provides a straightforward API for defining tools, resources, and prompts (for example, via server.addTool({...}) calls) and manages all the underlying protocol details. What sets FastMCP apart is the rich set of features it supports out-of-the-box: authentication hooks, user session management, image content handling, structured logging, error handling, SSE streaming, progress notifications, and even support for sampling (for more interactive, back-and-forth calls in MCP). It covers all aspects of the MCP spec so you don’t have to reinvent those pieces. Notably, FastMCP also includes a CLI tool that helps during development, such as running your server in a dev mode or inspecting it with an MCP client in the terminal, which is a big productivity boost.
Pros:
FastMCP strikes a good balance between developer-friendliness and power. Its API is high-level and declarative enough that a simple server can be written in a few lines (similar to EasyMCP’s minimalism), yet it doesn’t shy away from the tough parts of MCP. For instance, if you need streaming responses, you can configure the server to use the SSE transport, and FastMCP handles the event stream and even sends periodic pings to keep connections alive. If you need to maintain state across a conversation, FastMCP’s session support means each client session can have its own context or stored data. These capabilities make FastMCP suitable not just for trivial tools but for building more complex, production-grade MCP services that require authentication or long-running operations with progress events. Another advantage is its popularity — with ~700+ stars, it has an active community and plenty of examples available. It’s built in TypeScript on Node, which many developers are comfortable with, and uses libraries like Zod for schema validation, aligning with modern best practices.
Cons:
The flip side of having so many features is that FastMCP can present a slightly higher learning curve than the ultra-simple frameworks. There are more concepts to understand (sessions, different transport types, etc.) if you choose to use them. The documentation is crucial to grasp all options, though the CLI and examples mitigate this issue. Another minor consideration is that because FastMCP builds on the official MCP TypeScript SDK, it inherits any complexity or limitations of that SDK. If the underlying SDK changes, the framework will need updating — which is likely to happen quickly given its active status. Performance-wise, while Node.js can handle a good number of concurrent connections (especially with async I/O), it’s not as raw-speed efficient as Go. Running a FastMCP server at very large scale might require typical Node scaling strategies like clustering or multiple instances behind a load balancer. Finally, it’s a community project, so it’s not an “official” vendor-backed solution, although community support appears robust.
Ideal use cases:
Use FastMCP when you want a TypeScript framework that is production-ready and feature-complete. It’s an excellent choice if you foresee needing streaming results, multi-step interactions, or user-specific sessions in your MCP server. For example, if you’re building an MCP server that interfaces with a database and you want to maintain a transaction per session, FastMCP can do that. It’s also a top pick for those who prefer TypeScript and want to remain within the Node ecosystem while needing more features than a bare template or simpler framework provides. In scenarios where quick prototyping might evolve into a production service, starting with FastMCP can save you from rewrites later.
4. Foxy Contexts (Golang) — Declarative Go Framework with Dependency Injection
Foxy Contexts is a Go library aimed at developers who want the performance and safety of Go while enjoying a high-level framework to build MCP servers. It brands itself as a way to build MCP servers declaratively in Golang. Practically, this means you define your MCP tools, resources, and prompts as Go structs or functions and register them with a Foxy application builder. Under the hood, Foxy uses Uber’s Fx dependency injection framework, allowing you to inject common services like database connections or configuration into your tools easily. This pattern encourages a clean separation of concerns: each tool or resource declares what it needs via DI and what it provides for MCP functionality. Foxy Contexts supports both STDIO and SSE transports and even provides a testing package (foxytest) to facilitate integration tests for your MCP server logic.
Pros:
The biggest draw for Foxy Contexts is performance with structure. Go is known for its efficiency and concurrency — a Go-based MCP server can handle many simultaneous requests on modest hardware with low latency. Foxy adds a well-thought-out architecture using dependency injection, which makes it easy to extend or modify components and reuse code. This approach simplifies injecting dependencies (like S3 clients or databases) and makes testing easier by swapping out dependencies for mocks. In terms of extensibility, Foxy’s design allows adding middleware-like behavior by injecting wrapper functions or using Fx’s lifecycle hooks. It is very flexible if you’re familiar with Go patterns, and it supports advanced MCP features such as resource providers (dynamic resources) with upcoming enhancements for sampling and roots.
Cons:
Go and dependency injection come with higher upfront complexity compared to scripting languages or simplistic frameworks. A developer not used to Go’s compile-run cycle or concepts like DI might find Foxy challenging. There’s more ceremony in defining types and struct tags (to specify JSON schema for tool inputs) than in dynamic languages. Although the documentation is decent, the project is relatively young with a small community, so there may not be as many tutorials or Q&A solutions available. Additionally, because Foxy is a library rather than a complete server binary, you will need to write a main.go and manage the build process, which is standard for Go but less one-click than some CLI-based frameworks. Foxy’s use of Fx ties your application’s structure to that framework; developers unfamiliar with Fx might have to learn its conventions, though using Foxy without full DI is still possible. In summary, ease-of-use is sacrificed for performance and maintainability, which may be a worthwhile tradeoff if your team has strong Go expertise.
Ideal use cases:
Foxy Contexts is ideal when performance is critical or when Go is the preferred language. If you’re deploying an MCP server expected to handle high request volumes or needing low execution overhead (for example, an internal tool repository for many AI agent users), Go is a great choice. Foxy gives you the structure to avoid writing everything from scratch and is well-suited for integrating MCP functionality into a larger Go system. Choose Foxy if your team is comfortable with Go and wants a scalable, testable, and maintainable codebase for MCP over the long term.
5. Higress MCP Server Hosting (Go with Envoy WASM) — Enterprise Gateway Solution
The Higress MCP server support is quite different from the other frameworks: it’s not exactly a library you use in your app, but rather a way to host MCP servers within an Envoy-based API Gateway (Higress) via WebAssembly plugins. Higress is an open-source gateway that handles routing, authentication, rate limiting, and more for APIs. The Higress team extended it so that you can run MCP server code (written in Go, compiled to WASM) as plugins. In simpler terms, you write a Go module following their MCP plugin SDK, and then deploy it to the gateway; the gateway then exposes that MCP server to the world with all its infrastructure. The official guide highlights benefits like unified authentication, fine-grained rate limiting, audit logging, and observability for each MCP tool call — essentially, you get production-ready “surroundings” for free by piggybacking on the gateway’s capabilities.
Pros:
Higress’s approach is excellent for enterprise or cloud deployments where strong security, monitoring, and scaling are required from the start. By hosting within the gateway, your MCP server automatically benefits from features like JWT authentication, ACLs, and IP filtering without needing to write that logic. Additionally, metrics and logs for each tool invocation are captured by the gateway for centralized monitoring. Performance is another advantage: Envoy is highly optimized, and WASM plugins run in a sandbox with near-native speed. This makes an MCP server on Higress capable of handling significant traffic and leveraging Envoy’s asynchronous, non-blocking I/O model — comparable to a pure Go server. Enterprise backing (Alibaba) suggests long-term support and updates as the MCP spec evolves.
Cons:
The main drawback is complexity and specificity. To use this solution, you need to operate a Higress gateway, which isn’t trivial for a small project. It’s best suited for a cloud/server environment with Kubernetes or VMs. Writing a WASM plugin in Go is more involved than a standard Go application — you must follow the Higress plugin project structure, compile to WASM, and ensure compatibility with WASM constraints. Debugging such a plugin can be more challenging. Additionally, flexibility in choosing how your MCP server runs is limited, as the gateway enforces certain configurations (such as HTTP+SSE transport). Extensibility means relying on gateway plugins; adding new middleware might require additional WASM modules or configuration changes. Community use is relatively small outside of Alibaba’s ecosystem, so support might be more limited.
Ideal use cases:
Higress MCP hosting is tailored for production environments that already use (or are willing to adopt) an API gateway. It is ideal when security and governance are top priorities — for instance, if an AI assistant’s tools must adhere to strict security audits. If you plan to host many MCP servers and require centralized management, the gateway approach is beneficial. It’s best for enterprise-grade deployments rather than experimental or small-scale applications.
6. MCP-Framework (TypeScript) — Fast Project Setup and Auto-Discovery
MCP-Framework is a TypeScript framework that prioritizes developer speed and a “batteries-included” architecture. Its tagline is building MCP servers with elegance and speed in TypeScript. What this translates to is a framework that sets up a lot for you: it has a CLI that can generate a new project scaffold in one command (including a ready-to-go project structure and configuration), and it automatically discovers any tools, resources, and prompts you create by convention so that you don’t need to manually register them. Under the hood, MCP-Framework relies on the official MCP SDK for TypeScript, ensuring it stays aligned with the spec. It supports multiple transports — standard I/O, SSE, and HTTP streaming — so you can deploy servers locally or remotely with ease. The framework provides convenient base classes or decorators to define tools and other components, focusing on making your code concise and readable. It even has built-in handling for SSE authentication tokens to secure your server if needed.
Pros:
The standout advantage of MCP-Framework is rapid development. You can “get started with your first server in under 5 minutes” thanks to its CLI, which eliminates setup friction. This allows you to focus on writing tool logic rather than wiring up the server. The auto-discovery feature reduces boilerplate; you can add a new tool class file, and the framework loads it automatically. This is great for organizing larger servers with many tools, as each tool can live in its own module without cluttering a central registration file. Additionally, by leveraging the official MCP SDK, the framework inherently supports the breadth of MCP features and remains in sync with the spec as it evolves. The inclusion of both SSE and HTTP transports means it is future-proofed for upcoming changes to MCP’s networking. Community activity is strong, with Discord support and active discussions.
Cons:
MCP-Framework’s high level of automation means you need to learn its conventions. If you prefer explicit code over “magic,” this might be a slight drawback, as you must understand the expected file structures and class interpretations. Its abstractions (base classes and decorators) add another layer on top of the MCP SDK, so if something goes wrong, you might need to dig into the framework code or revert to the SDK directly. While the design is straightforward, extremely custom behavior may require workarounds, such as overriding the entire server initialization process. Performance is standard for Node.js — acceptable for most use cases but not tuned for extreme scenarios. Finally, being tied to the official SDK means that you need to keep an eye on updates as the spec evolves, but this is generally manageable given the active community.
Ideal use cases:
MCP-Framework is an excellent choice for developers who want a fast, structured start and are comfortable in the Node/TypeScript world. If you’re creating an MCP server project from scratch rather than integrating into an existing app, the CLI’s scaffold can save a lot of time. It is particularly suitable if you anticipate writing numerous tools or handling a complex domain — the conventions help keep your code organized. In short, MCP-Framework focuses on productivity and maintainability while ensuring alignment with the official MCP spec.
7. Quarkus MCP Server SDK (Java) — Embracing MCP in the Java Ecosystem
Quarkus MCP Server SDK is the official Quarkus extension that enables MCP servers in Java applications. It is essentially a set of APIs and annotations that allow Java developers to declare MCP tools, resources, and prompts similarly to how they would declare JAX-RS endpoints or CDI beans. For example, annotating a method with @Tool makes it an MCP callable tool, with the method parameters and return type defining the input/output schema. The extension handles all protocol negotiations under the hood. Being integrated with Quarkus means you get benefits like fast startup, live-reloading in dev mode, and the option to compile into a native executable. The SDK supports connecting via STDIO (for local usage) and HTTP+SSE (for remote usage), with separate artifacts to choose the desired transport. Notably, a companion project provides ready-made MCP servers (for JDBC databases, filesystems, etc.) built using this SDK, demonstrating its practical application.
Pros:
The Quarkus MCP extension is excellent for those already in the Java ecosystem. It lets you incorporate MCP functionality without leaving your stack, allowing for injection of services (like CDI beans) and reusing existing business logic. This is extremely powerful in enterprise scenarios, as you can integrate AI tools with your existing Java systems seamlessly. The simplicity of using method annotations minimizes boilerplate, and Quarkus’s developer experience (including continuous testing and hot reload) streamlines the development process. Performance is a strong point, with Quarkus leveraging Vert.x and Netty for high efficiency. Compiling to a native image offers fast startup and low memory usage, which is ideal for cloud deployments or scaling microservices. Being part of the Quarkiverse extension ecosystem also means long-term support and alignment with Quarkus releases.
Cons:
The primary limitation is that it targets Java developers — if you’re not a Java shop, adopting this solution solely for MCP might be too heavyweight. The learning curve for Quarkus and Java’s dependency injection might be steeper compared to simpler frameworks in Python or TypeScript. Setting up a Quarkus project involves Maven or Gradle and understanding Quarkus-specific development practices, which can be overkill for simple MCP servers. Java’s verbosity, while mitigated by annotations, still means more code than in dynamic languages. Additionally, the extension is relatively new and might not yet cover all edge cases, so for extremely specialized behavior, you might need to extend it significantly. Although community support is growing, the user base for this specific extension is currently smaller compared to more mature frameworks in other ecosystems.
Ideal use cases:
The Quarkus MCP Server SDK is ideal for enterprise and backend Java scenarios. If you have an existing Java system and want to expose some of its capabilities to an AI assistant, you can integrate MCP functionality directly without switching languages. It is particularly beneficial in cloud deployments, where Quarkus is Kubernetes-friendly, and for organizations that have standardized on Java, allowing them to leverage existing expertise and infrastructure. Its native compilation option makes it a strong candidate for microservices that need both performance and low overhead.
8. Template MCP Server (TypeScript) — Official Starter Template for Quick Setup
The Template MCP Server is not a framework per se, but a CLI tool and project template to scaffold a new MCP server project quickly. It is akin to “create-react-app” but for an MCP server. Running npm init @mcpdotdirect/create-mcp-server generates a ready-made TypeScript project that includes everything needed to run an MCP server: basic server initialization, support for both stdio and HTTP transports, a directory structure for adding your own tools/resources, TypeScript configurations, and useful npm scripts for development and production. The template uses the official Model Context Protocol TypeScript SDK under the hood and follows recommended best practices. Essentially, after generating the project, you simply add your custom logic (such as defining a tool function) and run the server in watch mode.
Pros:
The template is maintained as an official reference by the MCP core community, ensuring it remains up-to-date with the latest spec and SDK changes. It is incredibly convenient for getting started, eliminating the need to decide which framework to use or how to configure it — you receive a working baseline immediately. It includes dual transport support out of the box (stdio for local use and HTTP for remote SSE connections), making it great for experimentation and quick transitions from local testing to network deployments. Its minimalism also means there is virtually no overhead, and performance will align with that of the underlying SDK and Node runtime. For learners, it serves as an excellent starting point to understand MCP server construction with the official SDK.
Cons:
The template’s minimalism can also be a drawback if you need advanced utilities or a dedicated developer API beyond what the MCP SDK offers. After using the generator, you’re responsible for implementing additional features (such as authentication or logging) on your own. There is no built-in session handling or plugin system; you rely on the SDK for core functionality. Additionally, as a one-time scaffold, updates to the template do not automatically propagate to your project, meaning you may need to manually merge changes as the MCP spec evolves. Despite this, updating the underlying SDK can keep core protocol handling current, though community-specific issues may require extra attention.
Ideal use cases:
The Template MCP Server is ideal for developers seeking a straightforward, no-frills starting point that adheres to official standards. It is perfect for evaluating MCP without committing to a particular framework’s extended functionalities. It serves as an excellent foundation for building custom MCP servers or integrating MCP functionality into an existing Node app, especially when you want to study the core implementation details of MCP. For simple projects, the template provides all that is needed to scaffold and deploy an MCP server quickly, making it a practical choice for both learning and initial development.
Conclusion: Choosing the Right Framework
As we’ve seen, each MCP server framework offers a unique blend of ease-of-use, extensibility, performance, and ecosystem integration. Choosing the right one depends on your priorities and context:
Quick Prototyping & Simplicity:
Choose FastAPI-MCP (for Python) or EasyMCP (for TypeScript) if you need a working solution with minimal ceremony. The Template MCP Server is also an excellent starting point for quick setups aligned with the official SDK.
Feature-Rich & Scalable (Production-Ready):
For projects that may start small but need to scale or become complex, FastMCP or MCP-Framework (both in TypeScript) offer production-grade capabilities and a balanced, full-featured solution with growing communities.
Maximum Performance & Integration:
For raw performance or deep ecosystem integration, Foxy Contexts (Go) and Quarkus MCP (Java) are great choices. Foxy Contexts is ideal if Go is your language of choice, while Quarkus MCP works well in enterprise Java environments. Higress MCP hosting is the solution when enterprise infrastructure and centralized management are paramount.
Language/Stack Preference:
It’s completely valid to choose based on your team’s expertise. Python developers might gravitate toward FastAPI-MCP, Node/TypeScript developers have several options (EasyMCP, FastMCP, MCP-Framework, Template), and Go or Java shops have Foxy and Quarkus respectively.
In summary, there is no one-size-fits-all “best” framework — there is likely a best framework for your specific needs. Choose EasyMCP or FastAPI-MCP for ease and speed when you need minimal fuss, FastMCP or MCP-Framework for balanced and feature-rich solutions, and Foxy Contexts or Quarkus MCP for performance-critical, enterprise-grade projects. Finally, use Higress MCP hosting when you require robust API gateway features and centralized control. Evaluate your project’s needs, language preference, and scalability demands to confidently pick the framework that will make your MCP server development a smooth and successful endeavor. Happy building!
